04389nmm a2200685Ia 9781501705908DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979579644  a(OCoLC)980288440  a97815017059087 a10.7591/97815017059082doi  a(DE-B1597)473284  a(OCoLC)958095019  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aUA853.I75bB73 201704a623.45119095672231 aBraut-Hegghammer, Målfrid, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnclear Physics :bWhy Iraq and Libya Failed to Build Nuclear Weapons /cMålfrid Braut-Hegghammer. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b3 halftones, 3 line figures, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Security Affairs0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMany authoritarian leaders want nuclear weapons, but few manage to acquire them. Autocrats seeking nuclear weapons fail in different ways and to varying degrees—Iraq almost managed it; Libya did not come close. In Unclear Physics, Malfrid Braut-Hegghammer compares the two failed nuclear weapons programs, showing that state capacity played a crucial role in the trajectory and outcomes of both projects. Braut-Hegghammer draws on a rich set of new primary sources, collected during years of research in archives, fieldwork across the Middle East, and interviews with scientists and decision makers from both states. She gained access to documents and individuals that no other researcher has been able to consult. Her book tells the story of the Iraqi and Libyan programs from their origins in the late 1950s and 1960s until their dismantling.This book reveals contemporary perspectives from scientists and regime officials on the opportunities and challenges facing each project. Many of the findings challenge the conventional wisdom about clandestine weapons programs in closed authoritarian states and their prospects of success or failure. Braut-Hegghammer suggests that scholars and analysts ought to pay closer attention to how state capacity affects nuclear weapons programs in other authoritarian regimes, both in terms of questioning the actual control these leaders have over their nuclear weapons programs and the capability of their scientists to solve complex technical challenges.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aNuclear weaponsxPolitical aspectsxIraqxIraqxLibya. 0aNuclear weaponsxPolitical aspectsxLibya. 0aNuclear weaponsxPolitical aspectszIraq. 0aNuclear weaponsxPolitical aspectszLibya. 4aInternational Studies. 4aMiddle East Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  anuclear weapons, Iraq, Libya, nuclear weapons program, Middle East.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2016z9783110485189oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170590840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501705908423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501705908/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2016  aZDB-23-DGGb2016